    {
        "content": "<p>Ok, good. The easiest way of formulating this in Lean is to prove that for all <code>k</code> there is <code>n &gt;k</code> such that <code>6*n+1</code> is prime (and similarly for <code>-1</code>).</p>",
        "id": 499461843,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1739450239
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Without bothering with filters/infinite sets.</p>",
        "id": 499461887,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1739450252
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>All primes &gt; 3 can be expressed in the form 6n + 1 or 6n - 1. So this implies that there are infinitely many n such that 6n + 1 or 6n - 1 are prime. QED. No?</p>",
        "id": 499461915,
        "sender_full_name": "Kajani Kaunda",
        "timestamp": 1739450260
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"130384\">Riccardo Brasca</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Help.20with.20Lean.20coding/near/499461843\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Ok, good. The easiest way of formulating this in Lean is to prove that for all <code>k</code> there is <code>n &gt;k</code> such that <code>6*n+1</code> is prime (and similarly for <code>-1</code>).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So how do I do that? Remember, I am not so good with Lean! <span aria-label=\"smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f642\" role=\"img\" title=\"smile\">:smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 499462284,
        "sender_full_name": "Kajani Kaunda",
        "timestamp": 1739450344
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"734946\">Kajani Kaunda</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Help.20with.20Lean.20coding/near/499461915\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>All primes &gt; 3 can be expressed in the form 6n + 1 or 6n - 1. So this implies that there are infinitely many n such that 6n + 1 or 6n - 1 are prime. QED. No?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>No, it implies that <em>at least</em> one of the two set is infinite, not that both are.</p>",
        "id": 499463325,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1739450664
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah sorry, you want the statement with <code>or</code>, so then yes, it's a direct consequence of the fact that there are infinitely many primes.</p>",
        "id": 499463437,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1739450701
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So can we use the already formalized theorem on that to prove our case?</p>",
        "id": 499463588,
        "sender_full_name": "Kajani Kaunda",
        "timestamp": 1739450749
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So you've got a set you know to be infinite (the primes &gt;3), a set you'd like to prove is also infinite (the n s.t. ...) and a function from the primes to the corresponding n (somewhat implicitly given). The missing part is that this function is injective</p>",
        "id": 499463804,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1739450806
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"307953\">Ruben Van de Velde</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Help.20with.20Lean.20coding/near/499463804\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>So you've got a set you know to be infinite (the primes &gt;3), a set you'd like to prove is also infinite (the n s.t. ...) and a function from the primes to the corresponding n (somewhat implicitly given). The missing part is that this function is injective</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes Sir. The injective part...</p>",
